Node.Notes: Division between those who transliterate the following words as proper names and those who change the words to yield some meaning like "I am weary, O God; I am weary, O God, and worn out."
Uncertain, but leech is probably best guess.
Uncertain. Probably "give." May be what the daughters say or the names of the daughters,
Figurative for her cleaning up/removing evidence after her adultery.
Literally, "a hated woman." Could be just a woman who has yet to find a husband to love her or a hated/unpopular woman.
Literally, "wise trained in wisdom," which is something like "extremely wise." The LXX has "wiser than the wise."
Apparently "girded of loins," which is obscure. Most follow ancient translations with something like "strutting cock/rooster."
Unknown. Conservative approach is to separate word in two to yield "no rising" (i.e., no revolt against him). Most go with something with "a king with his army around him."
May refer to arrogant behavior or boasting.
Could be plotting evil or simple planning.
